le Dutch <i>drake</i>) ‘dragon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Duck","meanings":["English: variant of   Duke  .","Irish: adoption of the English name (see 1 above) as an equivalent of <b>Lohan</b> (an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Leocháin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Leochán</i>’) by mistranslation, as if from <i>lacha</i> ‘duck’.","North German (also <b>Dück</b>) and German (<b>Dück</b>): see   Dueck  ."]},{"name":"Drakes","meanings":["English: variant of   Drake  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","English: habitational name from Drax (Yorkshire). The placename probably derives from Old English <i>dræg</i> ‘portage, place where boats are dragged’ or <i>dræg</i> ‘drag net’, influenced by Old Norse <i>drag</i> ‘portage’, with a plural <i>drages</i> being shortened to <i>drags</i>, <i>Drax</i>.","In some cases perhaps an Americanized form of some similar (like-sounding) cognate in some other language."]}]},{"name":"Lord","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably a respelling of   Laura  , that coincides in form with the German spelling of the same name and also with the medieval English given name."],"variants":[]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Lord John Drake was born about 1362, in Drakestown, County Meath, Ireland. He had at least 1 daughter with Mrs. Lord John Drake. He died in 1422, in his hometown, at the age of 61."},"et":{"about 1362–1422":"umbes 1362–1422","1366–Female":"1366–Surnud","1388–1446":"1388–1446","1362–1422":"1362–1422","1446":"1446","1422":"1422","1388":"1388","1366":"1366","1362":"1362","abou